The paper deals with stochastic combinatorial optimization problems, which are typically studied in the subfield of algorithms and data structures (cs.DS). The paper also uses techniques from probability theory and information theory, making it relevant to the subfields of game theory (cs.GT), machine learning (cs.LG), information theory (cs.IT), and computational complexity (cs.CC).
